# Gen AI Design Pattern Inspired by Art 

## Embracing Narrow Workflows for Success

Gen AI is capable of many things. Whether it’s writing code, generating images or writing technical documents, it can do it. However, capabilities don’t necessarily solve problems. Getting Gen AI applications to reliably solve a user’s problem is challenging. One of the reasons is because we try to have a one-size-fits-all approach, which often falls short. 

I had an insight when working on a personal project into why this might be the case. In art, where realism and abstraction demand distinct techniques, a different process is followed to come to a result. Atleast, that’s what I assume. If you would want to create a mondrian, you’d have to follow a completely different workflow compared to creating a drawing of a photo-realistic ladybug. For the user, the same holds true. If you want to have a painting of a mondrian, you would be wise to go to someone who is specialized in such styles.

![][image1]![][image2]

However, when it comes to Gen AI we tend to see things differently. We want to build generic applications which solve many problems. I don’t think we are at that point yet. For now, to add value and solve user’s problems we have to create narrow, deterministic workflows. Those workflows benefit from a trade-off in compute and the quality of the result. Essentially, if you increase computation (i.e. the number of model invocations), you’d likely end up with a better quality result. Combining these two insights enable you to create narrow workflows that tend to be reliable, while solving the user’s problem.

Essentially, adopting narrow, deterministic workflows, can lead to more reliable and effective AI outcomes.

**The Gen AI Design Pattern:**

* **Narrow Workflows for Precision:**  Just as an artist focuses on specific details to achieve photorealism, narrow AI workflows excel at solving one task exceptionally well. This targeted approach ensures reliability and determinism.  
* **Avoiding Generic Pitfalls:** Generic workflows, attempting to address multiple use cases, often result in unreliable and stochastic outcomes. By embracing specificity, we can mitigate these risks and enhance AI performance.  
* **Iterative Refinement:**  Similar to an artist layering colors and refining brushstrokes, AI workflows can incorporate iterative steps. Each step builds upon the previous, allowing for error correction and progressive improvement of results.
